of women’s roles in the creation, production, and consumption of art have reached us. This book seeks to write Block and her contributions into the art and cultural history of the seventeenth-century Netherlands, highlighting the need for and advantages of a multifaceted approach to research on early modern women. Examining Block’s achievements, relationships, and objects reveals a woman who was independent, knowledgeable, self-aware, and not above self-promotion. Though her gender brought few opportunities and many barriers, Agnes Block succeeded in fashioning herself as Flora Batava, a liefhebber at the intersection of art and science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt, Dutchy17th centuryxCollectors and collecting. 0aFashion and art. 0aFeminism and artzNetherlandsxHistoryy17th century. 0aFeminism and art. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aCultural Studies. 4aDutch and The Netherlands. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aWomen and natural history.  awomen participation in networks, women collectors, women cultural producers, women in knowledge communities.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102374840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048557677?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048557677423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048557677/original  a978-3-11-102374-8  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles